🎯 Ultra-Concise Interview Version (60 seconds)
In one system, we had live streaming traffic across multiple protocols flowing through Dataflow into Kafka and BigQuery, and several legacy endpoints were migrated to new IPs. I built a real-time validation framework using sliding windows to correlate Kafka and BigQuery events, accounting for out-of-order delivery and eventual consistency. The framework was protobuf-schema aware, multi-tenant safe, and production-shadowed. It caught silent routing and schema regressions before rollout and became the standard pipeline validation layer for future migrations.

How did you validate messages actually reached Kafka?

I used consumer groups dedicated to validation that subscribed to the same topics as downstream services. For every test traffic batch, I correlated producer-side message IDs with Kafka offsets and partition keys, then validated arrival counts, ordering guarantees per partition.

How did you validate Kafka → BigQuery consistency in real time?

Answer:
I used time-windowed correlation — Kafka ingestion timestamps were bucketed into sliding windows and matched against BQ ingestion_time fields. Instead of strict ordering, I validated count parity, schema integrity, and checksum equality within each window to handle out-of-order and late arrivals.

How did you validate multi-tenant isolation?
Answer:
Every message carried org_id and routing metadata. My framework asserted partition affinity and topic-level routing rules and ensured no cross-org leakage by verifying Kafka headers and downstream BQ partitions.

How did you deal with Kafka’s at-least-once delivery and duplicates?
Answer:
I implemented idempotent validation using deterministic event IDs derived from business keys + timestamp buckets. Within each sliding window, I de-duplicated messages before comparison, allowing us to distinguish between retry duplication and true data loss.

